Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law on the introduction of administrative liability for violation of the term and procedure for payment for goods (works, services) in the course of procurement for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to solve a very acute problem of non-fulfillment of obligations by customers in state and municipal procurement.
Until two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not get paid under already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General's Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who entered into unfunded contracts, tried in every possible way to evade their payment obligations, and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the prosecutor's office has made 9,700 recommendations, following the results of their consideration, 4,500 officials have been disciplined, 533 have been administratively prosecuted, 75 materials have been submitted to investigative bodies for the organization of procedural checks, and criminal proceedings have been instituted in 46 of them.
As a result, more than 66 billion roubles of debt to entrepreneurs was repaid.
And these huge sums have not been accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in payments to entrepreneurs for far more modest amounts have led to staggering debts.
Here is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a tender for the provision of social transportation services for several million roubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial pile of debts on wages, taxes, and loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not appealed to the prosecutor's office for help.
The problem has now been minimized in a number of regions.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts identified by prosecutors of constituent entities of the Russian Federation amounted to about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor's office operates in a manual crisis management mode.
The Prosecutor General personally conducts on-site meetings with representatives of local authorities, at which all violations discovered by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are thoroughly examined.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On introducing amendments to the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with regard to the establishment of administrative liability of the customer's officials for violation of the term and procedure for payment for goods (works, services) during procurement for state and municipal needs," which was signed by the President of Russia last week, will improve the payment discipline of public customers qualitatively.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General's Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand roubles for violation by an official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment for goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
If the official has already been subject to an administrative penalty for a similar offence, he or she will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative innovations in practice.
Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning for people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racially motivated attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's Travel Warning, valid until August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors, and Missouri citizens to be particularly vigilant and to exercise extra caution when traveling in the state in connection with a number of suspicious racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and are cited here."
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the group was prompted to issue a travel warning by a recent Missouri law that made it more difficult for people to win discrimination claims, and that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately target minorities.
"You have people who are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of their skin, they are beaten and killed, "Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in Missouri, told the Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints more often than ever before."
This is the first such warning issued by the organization against the state of the United States.
The group referred to incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tori Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gasoline while traveling in the state, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also cites a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's Office, which found that black drivers were 75 percent more likely than white drivers to be stopped on the road.
"The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to alert their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared one way or another, whether they take the money with them for bail or tell their relatives that they are traveling across the state."
According to the latest data from the FBI's Hate Crimes Reporting Program, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, making the state the sixteenth largest in the state.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that will make it harder to sue a legal entity for housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after those states passed new immigration-control laws that ordered local law enforcement to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which the ACLU said should have increased the number of racial checks.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but civil-society organizations have recently resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
