Disneyland with the death penalty.
Why does Singapore abide by the law?
I'm talking to a local businessman, Chang, sitting in an open-air eatery.
Commenting on the situation in Singapore, Chang smokes one cigarette after another, and carefully stores the cigarette butts in an iron box seized from his office.
After the conversation is over, the businessman heads to the nearest ballot box - a hundred meters away - and throws the bulls out there.
The fine for littering in a public place is 500 local dollars, Chang said.
You know, since I was a child, I just developed a reflex: you can't throw a candy floss on the pavement, they will immediately fine you.
And now cameras are everywhere.
Indeed, Singapore's sidewalks in the city centre are as clean as a museum.
Chang says that three months ago, his neighbor's 18-year-old son painted graffiti on the wall of an old colonial building.
The court found the boy guilty of vandalism and sentenced him to flogging.
What?!
Imagine.
He was hit ten times on the buttocks with a wooden stick and spent a week in prison.
Corporal punishment is not uncommon.
How Singapore combines the highest standard of living and incredibly harsh laws, was examined on the spot by an AiF columnist.
No one here thinks about abolishing the death penalty, "explains lawyer Victor Lee Hong.
And the government has long been spitting at the opinion of both the EU and the US on this issue.
If a person transports a large consignment of drugs or trades in them, a gallows is put in place.
In 2002, a 22-year-old Australian citizen was arrested at Changi Airport carrying 400 grams of cocaine.
He has been defended by the Australian prime minister, who has threatened sanctions, international human rights activists, and even the Pope.
But the guy ended up being hanged anyway.
After that, drug couriers diligently travel around our country.
The fact is that in Singapore, the laws are enforced by EVERYTHING, not just the humble and the poor.
It doesn't matter if you're a millionaire, a deputy prime minister, a famous artist, or a resident of the European Union.
There is only one option: if half a kilo of cocaine is found in your possession, you will be hanged.
When you walk around Singapore and meet a bunch of warning signs everywhere, you wonder how many prohibitions there are in this city-state!
For example, chewing gum is sold only in pharmacies and can be bought strictly on prescription (!) by a doctor.
A tourist will not be stripped of his chewing gum upon arrival, but it is worth sticking "gum" on the subway, and a fine of 1 thousand local dollars will be imposed.
In four days, I met two people with white signs around their necks: "I was rubbish."
In addition to a fine, a person is often sentenced to "banishment to the janitors" for throwing a gun past an urn: they clean parks and beaches for a week.
6 thousand roubles is paid by a "criminal" who forgot to flush the water in the public toilet, and when trying to alleviate a small need in the elevator of an apartment building, a special detector is activated - the doors are locked and a signal is sent to the police.
Exotic laws include bans on feeding pigeons in the street, public singing of songs, and even excessive watering of indoor plants (!): the abundance of water is thought to attract mosquitoes.
In order to avoid fires, smokers cannot carry lighters in the subway, otherwise they will be fined 5,000 Singaporean dollars.
In general, there is a thought: no matter how hard you try, you are bound to break something.
This is not the case at all, "Mohammed Kabir-Kajaria, the owner of a local travel agency, tries to dissuade me.
Particularly fantastic laws exist only on paper, and in the last twenty years I have not seen anyone prosecuted for violating them.
Why do they persist?
So that citizens do not relax.
Compliance with basic rules is strictly enforced.
For example, if a minor is sold cigarettes in a kiosk, everyone will be punished in a chain: the owner of the store will pay a huge sum, the violator himself will receive blows with sticks on the "back," and the seller will also be torn out and jailed.
It is precisely because of these stringent laws that offences in Singapore are rare.
Is this justified?
Back in the 1970s, we had chaos on the roads - motorists ignored traffic lights, drove as they wanted, got behind the wheel drunk.
After the introduction of fines for the year, everything calmed down.
Now the driver, having drunk a portion of whiskey, knows that if they stop, the policeman will not let go for a bribe, will impose a fine equal to the cost of the apartment, and will be sent to prison for years.
To many foreigners, the city-state in Southeast Asia seems like a kind of concentration camp.
In 1993, the American writer William Gibson called Singapore "Disneyland with the Death Penalty" - a guest from the United States appalled by the general wealth of its residents, its "eerily clean airport," and its "cultured nature."
They say that such things are unnatural, look artificial, and should not be so in principle.
It's early days in Singapore and you're rightly terrified of throwing a piece of paper on the sidewalk, stumbling over to the subway with ice cream.
But then you arrive at "Little India" and suddenly there's a "pattern rupture": plastic cups roll around the bus stop.
"How is that?" you wonder.
That's how it is, "the Singaporeans chuckle.
Anything happens.
Not every such "crime" will be caught on the spot, but you should know that if you are counted, you will not be ostracized, for you have broken the law.
More often than not, this is enough for a person to behave normally.
Of course, Singapore is quite authoritarian.
But you know what?
In Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam, I drove cautiously - motorcyclists often snatch smartphones and cameras from tourists "hands.
Downtown Paris is full of dirty bums and beggars.
On our streets, too, not everyone tries to throw garbage in the bin.
Singapore, by contrast, has become the quietest, cleanest, and safest city on earth, thanks to a set of draconian fines and ruthless (up to and including the death penalty) laws.
Think about it.
Such is human nature: remember, in Russia, no one was wearing a seatbelt at the wheel until they started to fine.
Although the main thing in Singapore is not fines, but voluntary compliance with the law.
And we should think that in Russia people would also welcome clean streets, no garbage in the subway, and would welcome the arrest of those who confuse an elevator with a public toilet.
So, thank you, no need for corporal punishment.
Otherwise, Singapore's laws are at least worth watching.
Nothing sacred?
Now the Trump White House is taking aim at the Statue of Liberty.
The surest sign of regime change is when it starts fighting the statues.
Americans understand this as well as anyone - hence the deliberate theatrical removal of Saddam Hussein's statue in Baghdad's Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration's key ideologues, no doubt knew what he was doing when he wielded the symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a heated argument with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president's proposals to sharply reduce legal migration.
To be fair, Miller did not attempt the statue itself.
Hordes of pleasure craft owners and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would lynch him if he tried.
But he attacked its meaning, and especially that attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the monument's completion, when Emma Lazarus's poems were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled at Acosta, "I don't want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the world.
The poem you are referring to was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty. "
Miller got the facts right, but as he said, it's not really about history.
This is about the current sound of Lazarus's striking words, the only ones in which the state invites not all immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / Your mobs dreaming of breathing freely / The miserable scum of your plentiful shores."
Never before have "unfortunate scum" been so visible on our screens.
Miller was not a literary scholar - he made it clear that these people were not welcome in Trump's America.
This debate about the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it is really a debate about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who fought to have her words placed on the statue's base after her death - knew very well that they were committing a very political act.
The sculpture was designed to mark the link between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female figure of Liberty.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a very different name: Mother of the Exiles.
Combining poem and image was a brilliant feminist move and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right did at least change it back.
The vociferous Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist who heralded the advent of Trump, reasoned in 2010 that Liberty does not invite anyone, but rather is an early neoconservative who carries the flame of America to a world in darkness: "Freedom goes forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the US. "
Against Limbaugh's wont, it did hit a spot.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
Lazarus's great creative achievement was to see her in the way that exhausted, unhappy, but hopeful people would see her on the decks of ships after a long and often arduous voyage.
This means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people seeking refuge and a chance at a better life.
Her statue answers them with the words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, that is not a prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is needed not to light the way, but to fuel the hatred that is their only source of strength.
