Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you're not prepared to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood the critical press.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism of him was, of course, irritating.
But he has not silenced his critics.
Because as early as 1783, Washington said, "freedom of speech can be taken away and we, the deaf and the mute, will be led like sheep to the slaughterhouse."
Now I turn to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and erased the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit null and void, and the online comment was written in the spirit of "well and what."
"It's just Facebook," many will say.
But it is also important.
That's especially important when you're talking about a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a Democratic-dominated state.
He is second in approval ratings among the country's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has shown a strong hand in running the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as a primary way to connect with his constituents, and jokingly shows off his balding post-chemotherapy head on his page.
So blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is purported to be an official public forum and run by administration officials with taxpayer money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Chez defended the governor's actions, saying blocking the comments was simply moderating them.
But it's all too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers, and haters riled by the Internet.
The Post spoke with some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And it is the real people, not the trolls - the teacher, the businessman, the pastor - who turn to their elected leaders.
They all say their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is Catholic.
Lakshmi's lawyer, Sarma Ramana of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment saying that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news," she wrote in the comments section of the Post article.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people post comments on the same topic, some immediately say that it's a so-called hoax, instead of admitting that they are dealing with a large group of disaffected citizens."
What the governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack," others would probably call an "active life stance."
In the Facebook era, it is easy to edit your image simply by blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
It is far less dusty work than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and silencing protesters.
But that is exactly what is happening now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not listening to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on the topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Casheris of Alexandria, the Loudon County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from his Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bevin is being sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It should not be that difficult.
In the days of Washington, the era of affordable postal spending was about as transformative as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
Even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms "Jurikola," "Valerius," "Belizarius," and "Portius" wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the online George Washington Papers Project, his office was inundated with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce, and Navigation.
But he was not trying to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent, and speech lies at the heart of our state.
And true leadership means accepting it.
