Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Golden Land
Bardina Degei does not use a stove when cooking her lunch.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai district in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually simply places the sweet potatoes, called the "note," directly into the hearth.
Half an hour later, the charred tuber is removed and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on an earth floor - she has no furniture - and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is rife here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many of the men in the village are unemployed, many drink, and there are still soldiers.
"No one dares walk around the village after five in the evening," she says.
It is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 following a controversial referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by raising their hands in public in front of occupying troops.
The current movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against Jakarta's government, which maintains tight control of the region by barring foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is abandoned; the journey involves an hour-and-a-half flight from Jayapura, the provincial capital, to Nabir, followed by a five-hour drive.
There is no public transport.
The town of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the roofs of corrugated steel are painted rust in a variety of reddish hues.
Few Indonesians made it here, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, Papuans worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes," says Degei, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on our bodies."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia's golden land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a mountainous province about the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua boasts an estimated $78 billion in forest reserves.
This wealth, however, entails one misfortune for Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military retains a suffocating presence there.
According to a New York Times investigation in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
Demands for greater autonomy by the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden sinew and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured, and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s amounted to genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
"We will lose everything," a report published in 2016 by the Brisbane Diocese contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture - particularly, another report claims, rape and electrocution - and violent repression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week," said Andreas Harsono, who researches Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts and bolts have tightened as Papua's resources have attracted an influx of settlers from elsewhere in Indonesia.
The province's 3.5 million people are 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from Indonesia's densely populated islands of Java, Sumatra, and Sulawesi.
Javanese stalls, "warungs," sell fried chicken and a mixture of gados and vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Locals are struggling to compete.
"Migrants have started to sell chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than the indigenous Papuans," explains Abet Yow, a 24-year-old native of Paniai who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, because of her job.
"As a result, Papuans - Papuan mum-mama (women) - have lost their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Panyai.
But little has changed in Papua, and locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice," Yow said.
In fact, just two months after Jokowi's October inauguration, Paniai experienced tragedy.
On 7 December 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas hymns at a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the darkness.
Terrified children told them to turn the headlights on.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebai, one of the soldiers took offense at their tone and returned with the four soldiers after a while.
According to victims and witnesses, the soldiers, who were drunk, chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government election commission building, and the situation escalated the next day.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of a local police station and a military command center to demand justice.
They brought ritual hunting bows and performed Waita, a dance by the Mee Pago Papuan tribe, running in circles and mimicking bird song.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
As the situation escalated, soldiers were told by internal radio, "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," according to an official document seen by TIME but not published in the local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kayame, head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, sensed danger approaching and appealed for calm, asking the crowd to disperse.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, a bullet suddenly hit my left wrist," he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who fired the shot, but says the bullet came from the direction of rows of assembled soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were lots of shots," he adds.
Local resident Alfius Jove was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Johannes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME magazine grimly.
"I saw he was dead... I kissed him."
General Yotje Mende, the chief inspector of Papua police, told reporters his officers were merely "defending" their base because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua police spokesman Pujo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
News of the killings reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an impassioned speech in Jayapura, offering his condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address Papua's historical abuses of power.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately, so that it never happens again," he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights abuses.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some occurred in the nineties or early noughties.
The fact is that we certainly want to address these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed, "he said.
Wiranto then retracted his remarks, speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, and said he had no plans to establish a complaints organization in Papua.
Instead, he said, "Everything will be decided through the courts."
Wiranto, who was charged by the United Nations with "crimes against humanity" for the deaths of more than 1,000 people in East Timor's bloody 1999 independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
Families of victims from Paniai received such statements with grim incredulity.
"I've been questioned four times in the last three years, but there's been absolutely no change," Johannes said.
"I'm tired."
Years later, he says, he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I am afraid that I will be arrested by the military, I am afraid that I will be shot."
His brother Jacobus also suggested that the residents of Paniai were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping bury the four victims.
"After we buried the bodies, the military came after me," he says.
The shooting has not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot dead villagers in neighboring Paniai district of Deiyai.
One person was killed and 17 others, including children, were injured in a clash between villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to help take an unconscious man to a hospital.
The man, Ravianus Dove, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to hospital.
Angry villagers protested outside the office of a construction site owned by the company.
According to police, villagers threw stones at officers, who responded with warning shots.
But locals claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) opened fire on the crowd and killed one person.
"We were so panicked, we were afraid of retaliation," Dominggu Badia, 29, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being rushed to hospital, told TIME magazine.
"I hid in my house for two days."
The Deiyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved be held accountable and that the mobile police brigade be recalled from the region.
Panic has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is causing resentment among the Mee, Moni, Dani, and Damal tribes scattered throughout the leafy central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend the rights of Papuans by staging sporadic attacks and kidnap raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM's top leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In retaliation, thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained by the military in Paniai in recent years under the pretext of "defending national independence."
Some never returned.
Among Papua's population, Paniai is considered a "sad, forgotten place."
Poverty exacerbates discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is equally unavailable.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly music, but also some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
Typically, they save most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold in the local market.
Ten tubers of the note cost just 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic disparities have widened between indigenous Papuans and the new migrants who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport.
The few jobs that do exist tend to go to better-educated and better-off migrants.
Papuans rarely have the money or skills to run their own competitive businesses.
"Young people don't want to stay in the village... because there is neither work nor money," says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps Papua out of the eyes of the rest of the world.
Moreover, restrictions on the international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Esquudy and Basil Longchamp were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with relevant organizations," despite being granted rare video permits.
According to Phelim Keene, deputy Asia director of Human Rights Watch, promises made during Jokowi's election campaign to lift media restrictions in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
"Now foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces of Papua and West Papua face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of press attention means that international pressure on Indonesia's government is largely confined to Papua's immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific states - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and Solomon Islands - asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the shooting in Paniai.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanata Nasir dismissed the group's statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights abuses."
Locals want more foreign governments to take notice.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the Dutch ambassador for human rights, Kijs Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, the locals broke their silence, pleading, "We want freedom," according to a source who also attended the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold a new presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting," said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai, apart from living in the shadow of a greedy army, are mired in poverty, and their education and health care are poor.
Gobai says Paniai residents, like other Papuans, view their vote for Jokowi as a debt that he must pay.
"They don't need money, they just want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of defiance: burying the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never be done, they will at least not allow the guilty to forget their crimes.
"They killed a member of our family," Jacobus says without raising his head.
"What else did we have to do?"
