EPA chief Pruitt abandons plan to delay Obama-era emissions-reduction rules
A day after the 15-state suit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency reversed his decision to delay implementation of Obama-era regulations designed to reduce air pollutants that cause smog.
Pruitt attributed his decision to the fact that his agency is now more responsive to the needs of state environmental regulators than in previous administrations.
He made no mention of a lawsuit against his previous position filed in a federal appeals court.
The dispute revolved around the October 1 deadline by which states must meet 2015 ozone standards at the ground level.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay compliance by one year to give his agency more time to study the plan and avoid "misalignment with local decisions or impeding economic growth."
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma's attorney general before being appointed by President Trump, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since moving to Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly blocked or delayed regulations opposed by the chemical or oil and gas industries.
Wednesday's unexpected change of course is yet another legal setback for Puitt's path back to normalcy.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA chief had overstepped his authority in trying to delay enforcement of an Obama administration rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that by abruptly changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA's duty to work with the states to implement the new standards in a comprehensive and timely manner.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others, and discussed deadlines as part of the settlement," said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We do not believe in litigation regulation, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our statutes and the power they give us. "
However, the EPA statement said Pruitt may at some point again use his "deferral authority and other statutory authority" to ensure that the regulations are "on a clear course and with all available information."
Congressional Republicans are pushing for a broader review of the ozone rules.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states that filed suit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue the legal pressure.
"The EPA's change of course - after our lawsuits - is an important victory for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and the more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the smog that blankets their cities," Schneiderman said.
New York's suit was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone occurs when conventional pollutants from machinery, power plants, refineries, chemical plants, and other sources react with sunlight in the atmosphere.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in sensitive people, leading to thousands of premature deaths each year.
Health and environmental advocates welcomed Pruitt's sudden change of course.
"It's sad to think about how much pressure it took to get this perfectly logical step from someone charged with protecting the air we breathe," said Laurie Anne Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to resist the Trump administration's ideological campaign and protect air polluters and their special interests."
