The 1948 Ford Mercury drove past spectators in Monroe Village, Georgia, and roared toward the small Morse Ford Bridge.
As the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, approached the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its path.
The main one - a middle-aged man in a thin stripe suit - puffed on a cigar and looked through the windscreen.
Those inside trembled with fear.
"We need that nigger, Roger!" the man yelped.
"Get him out of the car!"
Shocking screams broke the silence as a young black man was dragged out of the front seat.
Fortunately, the gruesome scene, which took place on July 22, is just a staged one.
But when a noose was put around Roger's neck, almost everyone in the audience was really holding their breath.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to the Morse Ford Bridge to recreate the night in 1946 when the Ku Klux Klan lynched two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey.
No one has been convicted of the murders.
"It's amazing that in all these years, not one person has been arrested - even though we see them next to us; even though we know who they are," said Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
"It is a stain on our history and a stone on our souls."
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia congressman who has fought for human rights all his life.
For him, the show is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been redressed.
"We want an investigation, we want an end, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We cannot move to healing and reconciliation until we achieve justice."
A coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the lynching at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI records obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of participating in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always been acutely aware of the two linked motives of the vigilantes: politics and sex.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court ruled for the first time that black citizens could vote in primaries that summer.
Around the same time, according to FBI reports, a black man, Roger Malcolm, stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says rumors circulating in the city that Hester was sleeping with Malcolm's wife Dorothy, and that the baby she was due to give birth to was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove from the prison to the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of vigilantes surrounded the car.
"It turns out that Harrison organized and commanded the murders," one FBI report concludes.
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and city law enforcement agencies, who not only participated in the killings, but also destroyed evidence and withheld the identities of witnesses."
Brooks calls it short.
"It was an attack on voting rights," he says.
"They were all killed to send a message to black people in the city: if you register and vote, you will be the same."
For almost a decade, Cassandra Green has directed an annual play recreating that lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visually arresting and tells the story of a deep racism that many would like to believe no longer exists in America.
It's hard to watch and even harder to turn away, but Green believes that's what matters.
"We don't want to talk about Lynch courts because they show us our own ugliness," she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through."
Rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the first day nearly 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - gathered indoors and listened to a polished review of the play over the years.
Wade Marbaugh was a director with Green.
He played the role of a senior clan member for several years, but says the role never got easier.
"I feel like I got dirty because it's not the person I am," Marbaugh said.
'But I think it's important to remember this story because we don't want to go back to that time. '
Inside, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Ruscona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, are reprising their roles.
The play begins with Malcolm, furious that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, shouting and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Rascona shouts in response.
There is a bang.
And at the same time, everyone (at least the black actors) erupts in laughter.
Green laughs loudest.
"What is it?" asks Ascona.
He is concerned and embarrassed.
Am I overplaying my hand?
"No," Green says with a laugh.
"I just don't think whites were saying 'nigga' back then."
"Yes," laughs one of the black performers.
"You've got to call it a hard 'p'."
And so does the energy in the room: discomfort is replaced by a sense of camaraderie.
Everyone must do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the sake of the memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene starts all over again.
This time, when Raskona says the word "n," it is clear and sharp.
No one is laughing.
The play ends cruelly and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs the sad song "Strange Fruit" by Billie Holiday.
Her voice is interrupted by the word.
A hundred yards away, fifty spectators wipe tears and sweat from their eyes.
The audience is almost equally black and white.
One couple traveled from Ithaca, New York, to watch the show; many live nearby.
They all endured Georgia's heavy spirits for almost eight hours as Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until then, the killings were only history, but now that they stand in the same place where they lynched people, it seems that their ghosts hang in the air.
When the last note of the song subsides, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children bend over to their heads, touch blood paint and still bodies, and whisper to each other.
"They're not really dead," mutters one little boy, as if to remind himself.
A few minutes later, Green thanks the audience, and all of a sudden it's over.
Actors throw ropes off their necks and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the main puppeteer.
Nick Raskona embraces the other two actors and suddenly, weeping, falls into their arms: the emotional burden of the performance finally falls on him.
"It's all right," whispers one of the women.
"We know you have a good heart.
You had your reasons for doing so. "
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta animatedly discuss the performance with a black couple they had just met.
Denisa Daplinsky struggles to find words to describe how she feels after the performance.
"It's hard to listen to those horrible, eerie words and actions... of people who look like you and who do it because they look like you," she says.
"After that, I think lynchings still happen," she adds, "but now it's called police shooting."
In the other corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks caught the attention of everyone, who recalled his work as a human rights defender at a meal.
He says he has already started planning for next year's performance.
"The production inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we went through, but also teaches us," he says.
'Because if you don't learn from it, it can happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it. "
