New test results to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden published
The latest test results for asylum-seekers in Sweden, who have been subjected to a new method of medical age assessment, show that more than 80 per cent of those tested were assessed as being over 18 years of age, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) began conducting tests earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment of asylum more accurate, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the true age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the forensic science agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were assessed as 18 years old or older, and in another 25 cases, the forensic science agency assessed that the person being tested was "probably 18 years old or older."
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was "probably under 18."
Tests are carried out only in cases where a person's age is in doubt.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with those of previous months.
"We don't see much difference from the statistics of the past months, the numbers are quite consistent," he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers have lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases, the "most likely age of the person being tested is 18 or older."
However, after examining 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases a person openly declared that he or she would turn 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which consists in taking X-rays of wisdom teeth and CT scans of knee joints and submitting them to dentists and radiologists for analysis, has also drawn criticism in some quarters.
One skeptic is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institut, part of whose work is to assess people's biological maturity to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than normal.
'I had reasons to think about it and I don't think we should use the methods of measurement that are used now.
Biological age is thus very imprecise.
If we can't identify it with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can, "he told Metro newspaper.
However, Göranssen of the forensic medicine agency has spoken out in favour of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, the risk of mistaking a child for an adult is small.
The biggest risk we face is when a person is about to turn 18, in which case they are about 10 percent. "
