How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules aimed at preventing unlimited spending by European football clubs will not prevent the world-record transfer of Neymar from Spain's Barcelona to France's Paris Saint-Germain.
Any repercussions could come further down the line, for Paris Saint-Germain, from UEFA, the governing body of European football, which has the power to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League tournament.
According to the financial fair play rules introduced by UEFA in 2011, PSG will eventually have to show that Neymar's transfer was financed without major losses.
Barcelona were paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to free the Brazilian from his contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
PSG could certainly splurge to hire Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars, given the team's financing from Qatar's energy-rich ruling family.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums to acquire players, but they have to balance that against legitimate sources of revenue in order to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs saddled with huge debts in their pursuit of success were, in fact, cheating and risking ruin if banks or owners stopped financing.
In 2011, the FFA stopped focusing on the clubs "debts and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model that Roman Abramovich initially used at Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with good potential and then spend heavily to improve the team and build a global brand - has become difficult to implement.
Clubs could face losses of 30 million euros during the current three-year evaluation period, which runs into 2018.
And, despite Platini's ignominious removal from the presidency in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Aleksandr Ceferin, remains determined to rein in excessive spending.
"Of course, the FFP is alive and moving forward, we will tighten the rules," Andrea Traverso, who oversees the FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay the buyout of Neymar's contract as a one-time payment, he can, for reporting purposes, spread that amount over the entire duration of his contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer value can be reported in the annual accounts as a cost of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of sanctions by the "FFP" in 2014, PSG, as well as Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City, were subjected to the heaviest sanctions.
PSG was fined €60 million ($82 million at that rate), which was later reduced to €20 million, and ordered to limit its Champions League squad for the 2014-15 season to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is tracking clubs that may try to outwit its financial inspectorates by inflating their revenue at the expense of companies linked to the club's owners.
Although a Qatari company could sponsor PSG, if the amount of funding were deemed to be in excess of standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to be considered legitimate revenue.
That is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the Qatar Tourism Authority's funding of PSG had been inflated.
It has been reported that part of Neymar's earnings at PSG could come from payments by the 2022 World Cup organising committee in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar will become a World Cup ambassador, and UEFA inspectors could easily detect such a maneuver.
Past sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will be even more vigilant against any attempt to circumvent the rules.
According to people familiar with the situation on Thursday, UEFA has not held preliminary discussions with PSG regarding the transfer of Neymar.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to discuss PSG's situation.
According to the latest published accounts, in 2015-1016, PSG earned more than €10 million in profit on turnover of €542.4 million.
The accounts for the last fiscal year have not yet been published.
"PSG" expects that the arrival of Neymar will become fertile ground for sponsorship deals, the sale of paraphernalia and t-shirts with the team logo.
The club expects turnover to rise by at least 30 per cent following the hiring of a new player.
Undoubtedly angry at the departure of one of their best players, the Spanish league tried to thwart the transfer of Neymar by claiming that PSG would violate the financial fair play.
"This is a clear case of 'financial doping', with club and state," La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Qatar as PSG's ultimate owner.
Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's doubts about state funding for the club.
"It is all the consequences of ownership and it has completely changed the landscape of football over the last fifteen years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"When a club belongs to a country, anything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to comply with the financial fair play, because a country can have many ways and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The order and places of the oath of office will be determined by the president
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law have been developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Building.
A week ago, the deputies planned to define directly the procedure for taking the oath of office in the law.
Children under the age of 18, as well as incapacitated children, will be exempt from taking the solemn oath, it follows from the revised text of amendments to the bill "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available to Izvestia), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
On June 6, during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin, President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of introducing an oath upon becoming a citizen of the Russian Federation instead of formally signing documents.
Deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for revocation of the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public incitement to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (Article 205.2 (2) of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for the hijacking of an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if this act is connected with terrorism (Article 211 (4) of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, its logic was as follows: when issuing citizenship documents, a person signs a promise to comply with Russian law - by embarking on the path of extremism, he violates that promise.
The bill was introduced to the State Duma in April by leaders of the Duma factions, Vladimir Vasilyev (United Russia), Gennady Zyuganov (CPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (Just Russia), and State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but it has now been revised once again.
Now it says that the order of taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, the parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation," indicating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting in front of the national emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where the emblem of the Russian Federation can be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state bodies of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could also be civil registry offices.
Those wishing to acquire Russian citizenship will take a solemn oath after officials check their documents.
But a person will receive a Russian passport only after taking an oath, it follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text states that Russia's oath will be from the age of 18, not from the age of 14.
The rule that the incapacitated or those with limited legal capacity, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read, or sign the oath themselves, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt "other persons" from this procedure,
The updated bill also stipulates a special procedure for admitting Ukrainian citizens who are considered native speakers of the Russian language into the Russian Federation.
They will have to officially renounce their Ukrainian citizenship by submitting an appropriate application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will have to be handed over to Russian officials.
Renunciation of "alien" nationality will not be required, as it is now, if it is provided for in an international treaty or if it is not possible "for reasons beyond the control of the individual."
A corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including First Deputy Speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Airat Farrakhov (all United Russia).
I think many of you know that it is impossible, simply impossible, to get a certificate from Ukraine.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for a decision on their fate regarding citizenship of the Russian Federation, explained Pavel Krasheninnikov, Head of the Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation (EP), the day before.
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on the employment of certain posts for foreigners will not apply to those who renounced "other" citizenship in writing and surrendered their previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "for reasons beyond his control" he did not cease to be considered a citizen of another country.
Foreigners are now prohibited from holding positions in the municipal service and from being employed in facilities and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring Russia's security.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country may not become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should enter into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
Nostalgia becomes niche in "Hot American Summer" and "Comrade Detective"
The current iteration of history nostalgically recalls both the characters "glory days in the 1980s; the grunge era in the 1990s (around the time that the great masters David Wayne and Michael Showalter made the sketch comedy" The State "for MTV); and itself - that is, 2001, before its stars like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler, and Paul Rudd moved on to more serious things.
As a cultural fact, it is both an exaltation and an embodiment of our age, with its constant reminders from Facebook.
But as a franchise, it seems anachronistic.
"Camp Day 1" was surprisingly good, and not only because of its absurd humor (including the original story of a talking vegetable can voiced by H. John Benjamin).
The result is doubled by the main joke: middle-aged actors play sexually preoccupied children who have just come of age, making the impossibility of returning part of the joke.
"Ten Years Later," with adults playing adults, has less deep emotional roots, and its parody is more haphazard, incorporating riffs from 90s stalker movies like "Hands Shaking the Cradle."
In one episode, the character gets an Apple Powerbook, four-wheeled roller skates, and "a bunch of other things from 1991."
Many plot moves are the same.
The kind-hearted Coupe (Showalter), now a writer, still hasn't reciprocated from Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) still hasn't given up his virginity.
And then there is the insane and dastardly plot involving Ronald Reagan (also Showalter), now instigated by George H.W. Bush (a tried-and-tested parody played by Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of the franchise is stepping back from it.
It's especially funny to see the eternally young Rudd singing Matt Dillon's song from The Lonely, whose character, former big man Andy, now looks like an old man.
The franchise's success could be brought about by random insanity along the lines of the recurrent series Seven Up, until it reaches what I think would be its logical conclusion: "Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later," in which, in the final scene, the entire company goes to the cinema for the premiere of "Hot American Summer."
"Comrade Detective" on Amazon appeals to a different type of nostalgia: Cold War memories from "The Americans," "Explosive Blond," or even "Glitter," with its images of East versus West struggles.
This comedy, created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka and directed by Reese Thomas, depicts a television film: a Romanian police drama of the 1980s about two policemen in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism, and the Marxist-Leninist way.
Starring Florin Piersik Jr. and Cornelius Ulitsch, Gregor and the idealist Joseph, their dialogues are performed in English by Channing Tatum (who is also an executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a brilliant idea.
But only an idea.
There are some visual jokes (police officers spend time watching a chess match, like Americans might watch football).
A team of famous voices behind the scenes - including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloe Sevigny - allows you to play a fun game of "guess the voice."
But "Comrade Detective" so clings to the plausibility of a clumsy propaganda drama - there's even a Ronald Reagan masked killer - that it often looks like it.
Six long episodes are drawn out, and funny doesn't happen very often.
If it had been shorter, Comrade Detective could have handled his agitprop satire better; for example, every time Gregor and Joseph arrive at the American embassy, two thick men sit in the lobby eating a pile of hamburgers.
To an imaginary communist viewer, this image suggests that Western culture can make a fat cat out of anything.
The fictional Romanian authors of the film are not so wrong: we do so even with our own recent history, and with them, too.
