Bank of England to keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce later that interest rates will not change after weak economic growth and weakening inflation dampened speculation of a possible hike.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish and left interest rates unchanged amid growing pressure on household incomes.
The Bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer members voting for a rate increase this month because weak economic growth weakened support for a hike.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its forecasts for an increase to 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018, and warned that pressure on household incomes will continue, while inflation is still expected to rise to around 3% in the autumn.
But the bank warned that rate hikes in the next few years would be needed to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said borrowing costs were likely to have to rise more than expected in financial markets.
Members of the committee also voted to abandon part of a huge package of economic measures launched a year ago in the wake of Brexit.
From next February, the bank will close its emergency funding scheme, under which it provides cheap loans to banks, although it has said it will now provide another £15 billion - up to £115 billion - as part of the plan.
In its rate-setting minutes, the Bank said: "The MPC's main forecast is that gross domestic product (GDP) growth will remain slow in the near term, while pressures on real household incomes continue to weigh on consumption."
On rates, he reiterated that stopping inflation would require "some tightening of fiscal policy," on a "slightly larger" scale than markets expect.
At the moment, markets are predicting the first hike in the third quarter of next year and another in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all increases would be "gradual" and "limited."
The bank's forecasts for an increase this year and next are lower than those made in May, which were 1.9% and 1.7%.
The Bank left unchanged its forecast of 1.8% in 2018.
Sterling fell against the dollar and the euro following the news.
The pound fell 0.5% to $1.31 and 0.4% to €1.11.
The decision not to change the rate came after recent disappointing growth figures dampened expectations of an increase; GDP then grew by 0.3% in the second quarter, compared to 0.2% in the previous three months.
According to the bank's representative, growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will start to increase slightly at the end of the year.
The Bank's latest inflation report gave little comfort to households hit by high inflation and very small wage increases, which it said would intensify pressure before easing.
The Bank added that fiscal policy "cannot prevent" a hit to wages in the next few years, but expects wages to recover "significantly" by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set for growth as a result of growing demand for British goods, driven by the weak pound, which offsets some of the lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were slashed to 0.25% last August in the wake of the shock result of the referendum on leaving the European Union, which caused the pound to fall.
The bank estimates that it will likely take four years to have a full impact on prices and the economy.
