NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
From September, patients will have access to a "revolutionary" HIV prevention drug following a High Court battle over NHS funding for the drug.
NHS England has announced that Pre-exposure Prophylaxis for HIV (PEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in at-risk individuals by an average of 86 per cent, will now be offered by the health service for an initial three-year trial period to around 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a High Court ruling last year that the NHS could afford to pay for PIP, despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed as a "major innovation" by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens, with the National AIDS Control Authority (NAT) calling it a "turning point."
Before the scheme is fully rolled out across England by April 2018, venereal disease clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start registering people, with many more joining in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) is a course of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Studies have shown that PEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among at-risk people.
When taking PrEP before sex, the human body contains enough of certain drugs to prevent HIV infection.
These drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Eligible patients include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are HIV positive and do not receive successful treatment.
The researchers will select eligible participants for the study, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals whose partners are unknown about whether their HIV status is being held back by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and registered with a general practitioner in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereal disease clinic participating in the programme.
The programme will cost £10 million, and NHS England this week signed a contract to provide the drug following an international procurement tender.
The study is designed to assess the full potential of PEP by collecting clinical data on who is the drug's target audience, its uptake, and its use on a large scale.
"This critical innovation should complement and reinforce the large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is yet another milestone in more than three decades of progress in the fight against one of the biggest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of the NAT (National AIDS Control Authority), said: "This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PEP, if properly targeted at people who need help and are at risk, could make a difference to the state of the HIV epidemic in England.
Beginning in September, people at risk of HIV through this National Health Service-funded study in England will have access to a novel and empowering tool that people can control themselves without discussing it with a partner, improving many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news. "
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now is to ensure that the trial is rolled out quickly across the country and that no one at risk of HIV is forgotten.
Now that we have the experimental drug PrEP, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV. "
Shadow health secretary Sharon Hodgson said: "We very much welcome the launch of the PEP trial, which has been badly delayed due to months of delay and delay by the government."
The data demonstrate how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and halting the transmission of this fatal infection.
This test will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PEP.
It is now important that the trial be rolled out across the country as soon as possible to protect those at risk of HIV and move us one step closer to halting the spread of HIV in society.
