In Spain, dismissed an official who did not go to work for 10 years
What angelic patience (or utter indifference to public service) should the Spanish official's boss, Carles Recio, have had?
Permanent truancy lasted for 10 long years.
Still, Mr. Recio was fired.
But not his immediate boss.
Which only in the world of bureaucrats does not happen.
Ordinaries, it seems, have long been accustomed to all the pranks of "servants of the people."
And yet officials always manage to surprise those on whose taxes they live well.
This time, the "sensation" came from Spain.
There, Carles Recio, a Valencia archivist, managed not to go to work for a decade.
At the same time, he received a regular salary.
And the whole substantial amount - 50 thousand euros per year.
And now, Mr. Recio's "wondrous times" are over.
He was dismissed by the Valencia Legislative Assembly.
The investigation revealed that a malicious truant would arrive at the office at 07: 00 every working morning to check in with the electronic system.
And then he went home.
He showed up at work again at 4 p.m. to note again on the system that he had left.
And so for 10 years.
It also became known that the truant devoted all his free time to drawing comics at home.
Now members of the Valencia Legislative Assembly are considering how to punish Mr. Recio's immediate supervisor, who could not help but know how to "actively work" in his workplace.
Judges offered protection from chairmen
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes limiting the powers of court presidents and introducing their election.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court is also due to submit proposals within the framework of the presidential commission.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the members of the Council.
At a meeting with the members of the Council on 8 December 2016, they discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see Kommersant of 9 December).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals that address issues ranging from ensuring the independence of judges and identifying miscarriages of justice to court funding and legal education.
One idea put forward by Kremlin human rights activists is to limit the powers of court presidents in order to increase the independence of other judges.
If a candidate for the post of judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, the president of the court, according to the HRC, should submit him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to assign cases to judges.
This, experts admit, can be done by a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the chairman is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the qualification assessment of a judge, initiate disciplinary proceedings against him or her, or take decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "the election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and to "endow them with powers of relatively short duration, with mandatory rotation."
Currently, all court presidents (from republican to district courts) are appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the Chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes a new organization of appeals and cassation in courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts rely on the practice of arbitration courts.
Under them, there are "judicial districts," which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use the "telephone law."
The HRC proposes to strengthen the magistrates of the Human Rights Council with people's assessors in order to consider certain "categories of civil and administrative cases" with their participation.
For example, revocation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, protection of honour and dignity, revocation of driver's licenses, etc.
"These are only our proposals," Tamara Morshchakova, a member of the Human Rights Council and retired judge of the Constitutional Court, explained to Kommersant.
She also recalled that the President's instruction applied not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the Supreme Court (the co-executors include the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation) to fulfill its mandate.
Chairman of the Supreme Court Vyacheslav Lebedev has until September 1 to report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of the judiciary is ensured in the Russian Federation.
Living the high life: The half-floor and clever design tricks have turned this small flat in Earl's Court into a spacious home
Joan Lee, a former banker with a passion for property renovations, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to a flat in Earls Court in 2014.
The flat is on the ground floor of a pretty Queen Anne-style house, and in favour of the new design is the fact that Joan has not packed up her things and moved again.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much bigger space," says Joan.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price the same day. "
Since first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally, it was a one-bedroom flat - you had to walk through the kitchen to get into the bedroom - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to make the most of the generous height of the ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands, "she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill-based architectural and design studio Duck & Shed to use 12.5-foot-high ceilings to create a home that would not only be a successful project, but also fit for Joan to live in.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a semi-floor where one could stand at full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
"Working with steel structures is very difficult," he explains.
"We had to arrange the rooms so that they were above each other and did not have to bend.
It was not just a matter of building a simple platform, but also of bending the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed the space to be used from above and below. "
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms, one above the other, in the allocated space - and much more.
From the half-floor, a vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" overlooks the chic living room below.
Mirrored furniture with gold trim, silver accents and vintage lighting from Serge Mooy set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror safety panel looks like a window into another room.
At the entrance, mirrored cabinets are used to store all Joan's crockery.
To create the feel of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block out the kitchen when it is not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding door, like in a garage.
"Engineering was involved here," Erfan says of the steel-reinforced wood-fiber panel door.
"It has a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slips very easily."
Thanks to the judicious use of space and storage, Joan was given an additional 16 square metres, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
"At the end of the day, floor space is what you will sell, that is, what your property is valued at," says Erfan.
"To put it bluntly, an estate agent will come in and make a calculation based on floor space."
Here, they were able to increase the floor area using quality materials that add a touch of luxury to the space.
"Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the home," says Erfan.
"Nobody falls in love with the wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not touch the strings of our hearts. "
This is a testament to the fact that the apartment can go from something ordinary to something stunning due to its good design and increased footprint.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
The Government has approved the establishment of a Commission on Cultural Policy
The Russian government has approved the creation of a commission on state cultural policy.
The relevant decree is published on the government's website.
According to the document, the main task of the commission will be to develop and adjust strategic approaches to the implementation of cultural policy.
The Commission will also develop draft strategies for cultural policy, clarify tasks and prepare new programs for its implementation.
Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation has been appointed head of the Commission.
The composition of the Commission will be approved separately.
In 2016, the Prime Minister of the Russian Federation, Dmitry Medvedev, approved a plan to implement the strategy of state cultural policy until 2030.
The plan includes 193 measures and provides for measures to expand the influence of Russian culture in other countries, preserve the common cultural space and cultural heritage, and will contribute to the creation of conditions for the development of culture in the country.
G20 inflation falls to eight-year low
Consumer price growth in the G20 countries has fallen to an eight-year low, The Wall Street Journal reports, citing data from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
The OECD estimates that inflation was 2% in June 2016, down from 1.7% in October 2009.
Earlier, Rosstat reported a 0.1% decline in Russia's consumer price index.
Thus, the agency recorded the first weekly deflation in 2017.
The inflation target in Russia, according to the Ministry of Finance's calculations, is 4.1%.
However, the Ministry of Economy believes that the target has already been achieved - according to the Ministry, the figure is 4%.
