The MFA was outraged by the blocking of statements by the UN Security Council on the attacks on the Russian Embassy
The Russian Foreign Ministry is outraged by the actions of individual Western diplomatic representatives who block statements by the UN Security Council in the press condemning the terrorist shelling of the Russian Embassy in Syria.
This is reported by the Russian Foreign Ministry.
The agency recalled that the territory of the Russian Embassy in Damascus was subjected to mortar fire for the third time in a month by terrorists of the Hayat Tahrir al-Sham (formerly Jabhat al-Nusra, banned in the Russian Federation) and Faylaq al-Rahman groups.
Taking into account that the international community is unanimous in classifying Nusra as a terrorist organization, and the UN Security Council resolutions call for counteracting this structure, the Russian Foreign Ministry noted that "it seems self-evident that Nusra's terrorist attacks should be met with universal unconditional and resolute condemnation, and there should be no ambiguity in the assessments of attacks against diplomatic missions."
However, as the diplomatic agency emphasized, "for the third time in a month, the diplomatic representatives of the United States, the United Kingdom, France and Ukraine in the UN Security Council, alternately varying the tone of their objections, hiding behind arguments about the alleged lack of necessary information, blocked the Russian Federation's proposal to adopt a standard short draft Security Council press statement condemning the terrorist attacks on the Russian diplomatic mission in the Syrian capital."
The unwillingness to show diplomatic solidarity with us should be on the conscience of these delegations.
"What is most outrageous is that the failure of the Security Council to condemn the acts of terrorists encourages them to carry out further provocations and terrorist attacks and gives them a sense of impunity," the Foreign Ministry said, adding that "we do not want these barbarians to be convinced that anyone in the Security Council is with them."
Vladimir Putin spoke out in favor of limiting the number of unscheduled business inspections
During a meeting on investment projects in the Far East, Russian President Vladimir Putin stated that the number of unscheduled inspections of entrepreneurs should be reduced to 30% of the number of scheduled inspections, and also spoke of the need to limit the duration of inspections to ten days.
"Unscheduled inspections are carried out, as a rule, without appropriate coordination with the prosecutor's office; only 2-3% is coordinated with the prosecutor's office, the rest goes on its own," TASS quotes the president as saying.
Vladimir Putin also said that investigators should be prohibited from seizing servers and hard drives at enterprises.
In addition, according to the president, business associations should have the right to defend the interests of their members in court.
"I hope that this will make a positive contribution to the consideration of cases related to entrepreneurial activity or violations of the law in the field of entrepreneurship," the head of state said.
As Kommersant reported, due to the moratorium on routine inspections, the number of other types of inspections of entrepreneurs is growing.
In May, a survey commissioned by the Business Ombudsman under the President of Russia, Boris Titov, revealed that routine inspections had actually been replaced by unscheduled inspections (the share of those confronted with them rose from 21.9% in 2015 to 30.8% in 2016), prosecutor's inspections (from 16.9% to 21.8%), raid inspections (from 7.9% to 13.3%), as well as inspections on citizens "applications (from 15% to 19.5%) and administrative investigations (from 10.8% to 15.5%).
