The brothers are competing for a real estate empire worth more than $500 million
Two brothers are fighting for one of Victoria's largest real estate empires worth more than $500 million - 40 years after their Italian ancestors founded a dynasty.
Former Carlton Football Club director and property developer Colin de Lutis lives in Toorak Palace three doors away from his younger brother Paul, who is suing him in the Supreme Court for the division of possessions and assets.
Paul has wanted to leave the family business since 2014, but a bitter divorce battle is still raging in the Supreme Court.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars since the family bought the Smith Street store in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a chain of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money has been invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's list of holdings now includes office buildings, development sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and Mount Buller, and shopping malls in the suburbs.
By arrangement with his late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as the De Lutis family's "main driving force and dominant personality" - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, while Paul owns about one-third.
According to court records, this means Colin's estate is worth $316 million, while Paul's is worth $176 million.
The division of property and money was a stumbling block for Paul.
"The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my view, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed attempts at reconciliation, the Supreme Court held its first hearing.
The brothers are now at loggerheads over who will control the existing business - from which Paul believes Colin has excluded him.
Colin claims this is not the case, but accuses Paul of mismanaging some of the properties.
In testimony given by Colin at the start of the trial, he said he hoped the dispute would be resolved.
"My Italian roots make me consider family a top priority," he wrote.
Legal costs are mounting like a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, emails, and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, and Charter Keck Cramer have been attached to the case; both parties have hired top lawyers, including Allan Myers QC, and top solicitors.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband, Luigi, were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950 "s, they have run dairy bars and gastronomy, and in the early 1970" s bought a store in Brunswick.
With financial guarantees, they bought a shop in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family jeans shop.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last year of school and Paul was a boy then (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says she and Luigi, who died in 2012, had hoped to pass their estate on to their sons without conflict.
"Luigi has often told me that he does not want the brothers to go to court," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group; Colina says Mark got $10 million when he left the business and Luke $26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "unhappy with the financial terms of their separation."
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL club's board of directors and, according to a 2015 biography by Eddie McGuire, the TV star's best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
The only response was from Colin, a text message that said that, as the case had not yet come to court, "I have nothing to say."
"I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and take the name of our family to court," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a deposition that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father would not like to see Paul and I argue in court," he said, adding that he "still hopes for a resolution."
On Friday, that hope seemed to have dissipated.
"Our case will be decided by the court soon," Colin wrote.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to the president.
Others tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly will actually succeed.
In that case, he would be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to President Trump, including news reports from the media - hoping to keep the chief at bay.
That's what reporter Josh Dawsey reports.
"In a meeting that the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, held with senior staff on his first day in office, he identified a major problem in President Donald Trump's White House that he hopes to address: poor channels of communication to the president."
Kelly told staff that information should pass through him - in paper form or through briefings - because the president would be better off making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is entirely correct, but others have already failed in trying to pacify Trump by tracking his communications.
President Trump's relationship with television dates back decades - and now that he is in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, resented unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to show him that he was getting fair coverage in outlets that could be persuaded," Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico at the time that "according to six former campaign staff members, in order to keep Trump's Twitter habit under control, one had to ensure that there was a constant stream of praise for him personally."
Good.
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habit has ever been "under control" is simply laughable.
Maybe these campaign staff members know something we don't - that, were it not for them, Trump's tweets would have been even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets that Trump did not post.
If his staff kept him out of trouble even a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has always been able to keep Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in a White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by giving Trump material - trustworthy or not - that confirms their views.
Politico - just for this story - wrote in May about advisers "penchant for peddling dubious information to the president.
Here is one example, described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Current and former Trump associates say that Trump can react very harshly to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
That happened in late February, when someone leaked to the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of the Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, accusing deputy chief of staff Katie Welsh of being "behind a series of leaks" at the White House.
Never mind that Johnson is forever banned from Twitter for aggressive behavior, that he has not provided specific facts, or that he has made false accusations in the past and then retracted them.
Trump read the article and began asking staff about Welsh. "
Goldmacher adds that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and Secretary of Staff Rob Porter "tried to build a system to manage and document the flow of documents that Trump receives."
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly is trying to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
Tyumen Prosecutor's Office Struggles with HIV Dissident
The prosecutor's office challenged the ruling of the Kalinin District Court of Tyumen, which dismissed a criminal case against a local resident whose infant daughter died of HIV.
According to investigators, the child died because the mother is an HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court exonerated her in connection with reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecutor's office believes that the crime cannot go unpunished, so as not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was brought under Article 109 (1) of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of stage 4B HIV infection.
According to prosecutors, the mother herself is HIV positive.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that the HIV infection did not exist," the Tyumen Region Prosecutor's Office explained.
The criminal case went to the Kalinin District Court of Tyumen, which on 25 July decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the dead girl, explaining that "he forgave his wife, he has no claims to her, she made amends for the damage and apologized."
The prosecutor's office disagreed with the court's decision and appealed, demanding that the dismissal order be revoked and sent back for a new trial.
The girl is dead, and it is impossible to make amends for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection, contrary to doctors "recommendations," the press service of the prosecutor's office reported.
According to the watchdog, she must be punished or other dissidents will follow suit.
According to the Tyumen AIDS Center, currently in Tyumen Oblast, about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care because of parental refusal.
"And this situation has already improved - during the year of work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat their children for HIV changed their minds - allowed for diagnosis, and began to take drugs," said Elena Loseva, a spokeswoman for the AIDS Center.
According to her, there is no legal way to influence parents, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with their children from hospitals.
How HIV Dissidents Are Dangerous
Late last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of Russia's first study of the so-called HIV-dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are defined as people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Medics and activists of AIDS service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and see their spread as a serious threat.
An eerie photo shoot that ended in tragedy took place on Thursday, August 3, at the Grecany railway station in Khmelnitsky.
A cheerful group of drunk young men strolled across the bridge over the tracks where the freight train was parked.
One of the friends had the idea to take a spectacular selfie on the roof of the carriage, Fakty was informed in the sector of police communications in Khmelnitsky region.
The boy began to climb down from the bridge to the train, but due to his carelessness he got caught on a power line and was hit by an instant electric shock.
Fortunately, the incident came to the attention of the station's dispatcher, who immediately called an "emergency."
Before the arrival of doctors, the victim was moved to a safe place, and then hospitalized in the burn department of the Khmelnytsky Regional Clinical Hospital.
The man was diagnosed with first- to second-degree torso burns.
Doctors are now assessing his condition as stable.
Law enforcement officials remind that lately, extreme selfies on the roofs of high-rise buildings, bridges, and moving vehicles have become increasingly popular.
Police are urging people to be vigilant and to avoid such photo shoots, especially among children and teenagers.
