Italy is taking a tougher tone towards NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
"If the NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin daily newspaper Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities seized a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually collaborating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organisation, which has been operating for just a year, declined to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
"For us, saving human lives is and will remain our top priority, so we very much regret that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone at this time," the organization said in a statement on social media.
"We will be able to assess all the charges now only after we have gathered all the information and been able to assess the situation."
Italian authorities have been monitoring the vessel, the Jugend Rettet, since October.
Its crew is suspected of taking migrants aboard in whole lifeboats, which traffickers sent directly to them, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the indictment, the contents of which were published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coast authorities, who control rescue operations in the area, more out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The code of conduct mainly assumes that ships of the Juventus type will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to abide by the code: Save the Children, Malta's MOAS, and Pro-Activa Open Embraces from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable as long as they did not entail any "meaningful change or impediment" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign are Nobel Prize-winning Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
