"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict"
The authorities of the Russian Federation have recently significantly stepped up their policy in the Libyan direction, and with their visits to Moscow, delegations from the opposing Libyan parties have become more frequent.
Lev Dengov, Head of the Russian contact group on the inter-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, Assistant to the Head of the Chechen Republic, told Kommersant what goals Moscow is pursuing in this region and on whom it is betting.
Little is known about the contact group on Libya that you chair.
Here is, say, a contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly are you doing, what are your goals?
The Contact Group was established on the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are overseen by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (a member of the Duma from Chechnya - Kommersant).
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker Mekhanik Chebotarev (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - Kommersant).
We thought about how to help the crew.
At that time, a contact group of military specialists and representatives of the State Duma was created, and our work was supported by the head of Chechnya, Ramzan Kadyrov.
And how did it happen that you led it?
As I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the team.
Our activities were not limited to the release of the sailors from Mekhanik Chebotarev.
We were able to establish contacts with representatives of all the main factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Saraj is based - Kommersant) and Tobruk (the seat of parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls eastern Libya - Kommersant).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Deputy Prime Minister of Libya - Kommersant), we were able to quickly negotiate the release of the Russian sailors.
It was then decided to establish a contact group to make better use of these contacts.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, and engage in dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I would like to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are in dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group, and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are now five members of the contact group.
Among them are people with experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to include representatives of the Middle East Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences in the group of experts on the region.
None of our staff is permanently in Libya, and there is no need to do so at this time.
Are there Russian military advisers and instructors in Libya right now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and publications about this are untrue.
But your contact group includes ex-military personnel...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities, such as Misrata (where the militias that played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar el-Qaddafi in 2011 and intensified markedly in subsequent years are based), that are closed to us until a certain point.
We arrived in Misrata in January of this year.
We were intimidated, we were told that all the Islamists and terrorists were there.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there for ourselves, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why such rumors are circulating, what the real role of the Islamists is there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the units that were engaged in the destruction of IS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the banned in Russia "Islamic State" - Kommersant).
We wanted to look at them, to get to know these people, to check the information that they were the ones who played a decisive role in the destruction of IS in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these achievements to himself.
And what conclusion have you reached?
Is it not Haftar who defeated the Islamic State in Libya?
It was not his job to do that.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And IS in Sirte has been fought by structures subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited to Russia the people who carried out this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April of this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and Rosguard.
You are, as we have learned, in all the Libyan regions, and you are probably aware of the sentiments of local elites and warlords.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the cease-fire agreements on the holding of elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj reached in Paris at the end of July?
Or again, as has happened so many times in the past, will agreements be broken, hostilities resume, and the parties try to seize power alone?
It is a good sign for us that Saraj and Haftar have agreed to another meeting, which was not so long ago impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
As for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, and many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and it was on that very day that Haftar boarded the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But Misrata did not believe the coincidence.
We were told: "You are probably very brave people who came to us today."
But our task is precisely to show that we do not support Haftar alone; we are engaged in dialogue with all the key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar communicated.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR facilitate mutual understanding with his Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And, by the way, does Haftar know the Russian language?
If he knows Russian, he knows it relatively well.
But what he has learned from us certainly facilitates dialogue with him.
And not just with him, by the way.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And now they speak Russian very well.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent nostalgic for it.
Do you think that the arms embargo imposed on Libya is likely to be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in supplying Russian weapons?
Interested, of course, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not like to arm some at the expense of others.
We would like to see everyone in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from Libyans for Russia to contribute somehow to its lifting.
Libya's constitution-making process is now well under way.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and reach an internal consensus.
Elections should follow, as Saraj and Haftar discussed at their meeting.
If elections are held and a legitimate government is finally elected (and neither side currently has this status), the question of lifting the arms embargo could be raised in the UN Security Council.
Raising the issue now is pointless and dangerous, and will only escalate the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees coming from Libya, feels abandoned by its EU allies.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its links with the Libyans?
Is it realistic, for example, for Haftar's forces to take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers transporting immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia's support, because Moscow is simultaneously engaged in dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misrata, and the south of the country.
Tribes in southern Libya play a major role here, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the southerners stopping the flow of migrants on the far side?
So, conventionally speaking, have the buses carrying Nigerian migrants been turned back?
That is what we are trying to achieve.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups have an interest in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help bring southerners together in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But, for starters, we would like to see Haftar and Saraj agree on this issue.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist who advocates the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How radical is he?
Wouldn't that be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about him.
In my view, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he holds the position that Libya should be a perfectly normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he is also active in the fight against terrorists.
Why does he have such a reputation?
It was created by countries that have no interest in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is, after all, the capital, home to the legislature, the executive, and the judiciary.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank, and other state structures.
Of course, some countries had an interest in keeping us out.
And we mixed all the cards with them and started actively communicating with Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the benefits: Rosneft has signed a cooperation agreement with Libya's state oil company, NOC.
NOC director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft chief Igor Sechin struck the deal, is himself from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do about it?
I think it's a resale.
And what other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
Plans are afoot to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar el-Qaddafi.
This refers, in particular, to previous agreements in the field of transport (the construction of railways), energy (electrification), and a number of others.
And the Libyans have something to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
So, just as in the case of Iran, is it an oil-for-services scheme?
I don't know what the scheme will be, I don't deal with these issues directly.
In fact, the economy is not the main issue for Russia in Libya.
We are, in fact, engaged in peacemaking there.
For us, the most important thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help Libyans come to terms with each other so that they can establish order and Libya is no longer a breeding ground for terrorism.
For Russia, this is its main task - to help the Libyan people and push out the terrorists.
Do you have any information about the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that, to date, not a single person from Russia and other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said that he had about 50,000 phone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - Kommersant), and there was no Russian speech there.
And from which states, then, do these militants come?
I don't want to go into those details.
Then we will formulate the question differently.
How many Libyans are among the Islamist fighters in Libya?
Libyans are almost non-existent, accounting for no more than 5%.
The rest are newcomers.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks along the lines of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
And when can such talks take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several visits are still to take place, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the talks.
