Michelle Carter Sentenced for Messages Inducing Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will have to serve 15 months of her sentence behind bars and an additional five years of probation.
Carter was convicted in June of involuntary manslaughter in the death of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father told Thursday's hearing: "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend. "
Carter was allowed to remain free pending an appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said both she and Roy suffered from mental illness.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict with her hands clasped and her eyes lowered.
"By her actions she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve herself.
She has denied responsibility, "she said.
'She's shown no remorse. '
But Carter's lawyer said it was a "tragic case for which she deeply regrets."
But Judge Lawrence Monis said he did not think her "age, level of maturity or even mental illness had a noticeable impact on her actions."
The prosecutor read a statement from Roy's mother, Lynne Roy, which said: "Not a day has gone by when I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I'm coping - I'm trying to support his sisters despite all the pain that will stay with us forever, "it reads.
Roy's sister Camdin Roy said she was haunted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"To lose someone who has always been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
The case is likely to set a legal precedent, as Massachusetts has no law that makes it an offence to advise a person to commit suicide.
Carter was 17 when Roy was found dead in his car in 2014 with carbon monoxide poisoning symptoms.
The case gained national attention when it was revealed that he had been driven to suicide by Carter's messages.
"You can hang yourself, jump off a roof, stab yourself I don't know many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death while he was holidaying with his family.
Minutes before her suicide, she wrote: "You should do this, Conrad" and "You just need to turn on the ignition and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted attention through Roy's death and banned her from speaking to the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
Legal opinion on this issue is divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, published a dissenting opinion in the Los Angeles Times that said, "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not jail."
