It has become a symbol of Provence and southern France, but there are now fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender has grown worse because of dry weather and disease-carrying insects, causing a constant headache for scientists and farmers trying to find a solution.
Eric Chez, an expert at the Provence-based agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, said: "Lavender in Provence is really under threat because in recent years the plant has been feeling the effects of climate change, with much less rain in the spring and especially in the autumn.
This affects the lavender's lifespan.
And then there are the little cicadas, leaf-hopping insects that carry micro-bacteria; in very dry weather, there are a lot of them. "
There is a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is in great demand in perfumery and cosmetology.
Eric Shas says: "Instead of very long ears with a lot of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weak or non-existent ears.
