The murder of the journalist underscores that Mexico is becoming increasingly dangerous.
The staff of the weekly newspaper Riodos usually meet on Wednesday to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in Sinaloa involving organized crime, corrupt officials, or the ongoing drug war.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told they had to change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children with them to an office where a grenade had already been thrown in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on a blackboard hanging in the room: enemies, neutrals, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - proof is not needed, suspicions and inner feelings will suffice.
They are drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being paid by the government or the cartels, a litany of villains who make the job of covering Mexico's chaos dangerous.
Violence provides no respite, and more and more journalists are among the country's multiplying corpses: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 have died since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection following attacks and threats; and at least seven people have died in seven states so far this year.
Among the latter is their publisher and co-founder, Javier Valdez Cárdenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violent drug crimes.
His absence is keenly felt, though his presence is ubiquitous - a large photograph of Valdez showing his middle finger with the words "Justice" hanging on the facade of the Riodos building; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramírez, wear T-shirts depicting his smile, face in glasses, or his trademark panama.
The seminar comes less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their shared trauma, nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was established in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, only two cases have been investigated so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of drug-related and organized-crime-related killings each year, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Riodos journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, even though they have been killed by grief, though it is now much more dangerous around them.
Without information about the killers, without justice, there is little use in talking about security at meetings, Ibarra said.
"It's very foolish to waste time on this seminar," he says.
"While we don't know the cause, we suspect everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdés left the offices of Riodos in the state capital of Culiacán.
He managed to drive only a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's name - which means "Twelfth River."
The gunman drove away in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdés was 50.
He is survived by his wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually quickly spread about Culiacan.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdés.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the US last January, Sinaloa has become one of the country's bloodiest battlefields, as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Let us not say that one or more people are killed every day in the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with the decorated two-story mausoleums of the drug kings, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Forget for a moment that a state of "calm" is simply when one of the cartels takes control of a coastal state with important ports and drug routes leading to the US.
Despite this, and the fact that Valdés was aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bojorquez, the 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, is crushed by guilt at not being able to protect his friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the killing.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the cartel's rival factions fighting Guzmán's sons.
The publication may have angered the sons; people believed to be gang members bought all the copies as soon as they arrived at the newsstands.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdés to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that was writing about the same story was seized.
Valdés was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroeste and founded Riodos with five colleagues in 2003, selling his 50-dollar shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without talking about drugs," Bojorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation as a bold and honest publication, with sales and advertising revenues growing.
Journalists liked to be able to report boldly without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to be able to read about things that no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Rio de Janeiro received the prestigious Maria Murs Cabo Prize for reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdés won the International Press Freedom Prize for his courage in investigating Mexico's drug trade wherever it led.
He candidly admitted that he was scared.
"I want to move on," he said at the CPJ awards.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is "a way of life," he said in an interview with Rompiento TV last October.
"You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist - either that or you're just fooling around."
I don't want to be asked, "What did you do when there were so many deaths around... why didn't you say what was going on?"
Riodos staff miss Valdés, the joker who swore like a port porter, the friend generous with hugs and advice, the teacher who knew how to get away with it.
They relied on the order he had established.
He had to wear his hat at all times.
He had to go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: has his love of the once-established order destroyed him?
His death also made them question their calculations about how best to do their job and stay alive.
"They don't like it when you look at their wives, their children, their legal businesses and their clandestine airfields for drugs.
"These things were out of bounds," Bojorquez said.
The result, even in the best of times, has been a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from anything that smells bad.
The problem, says the editor of Riodosa, Andrés Villareal, is that "the sense of smell can be deceived... and then what happened to Javier happens."
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa - as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero, and other states, where there is a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions, and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
Cell phones were suddenly banned from entering the room where Riodos staff had gathered for a security training, days before it was revealed that spyware, sold exclusively to governments, was being used in Mexico to spy on journalists and social activists.
Outside, two police officers take refuge in the shade of a tree in the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were assigned by the state government to guard the office of Riodos, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacán.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these policemen were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officers whom the governor himself said could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists traveled to a mountainous area that is under the de facto control of drug gangs.
In the next issue, "Riodos" counted on three main themes.
It is the killing in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
Then there was the exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor's hometown.
And there was a gang kidnapping at one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, a block from the prosecutor's office.
There was no official announcement of who was kidnapped or how, so care had to be taken when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was a favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and the authorities.
One journalist learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of government for most of the past century.
Recently, several PRI governors have faced high-profile corruption charges.
Villarreal asked journalists to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when "El Chapo" Guzman's son escaped a military raid.
Until a few months ago, readers would have been looking for Valdez's column with the most accurate information about the kidnapping.
"Before, we would have known what had happened," said 46-year-old Villarreal, nicknamed "El Flaco" for his lean physique.
"Today, all channels of communication with our sources have been severed."
Valdés's office is now being used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the murder of journalists, because the staff have become what they never thought they would become: activists acting on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramírez took some posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor's office dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the western state of Michoacán three days after Valdez was killed.
A burned body was found and authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists began to speak out, organize protests, and write "SOS Press" on sidewalks and walls.
Director Bojorquez was in Washington that day, seeking international support for demanding justice in Valdez's case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez was killed, Ramírez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their killings for telling the truth.
She then asked not to be given any more assignments covering the government for fear that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdés has said many times that journalists in Mexico are "surrounded" by organized crime, its accomplices in the government, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not just killed by drug gangs; they do so on the orders of politicians and security services in collusion with organized crime.
The Committee to Protect the Press, Article 19, estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
"In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up," says Ramírez.
Of course, the killings scare people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note, allegedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel, was found on her body: "I am here because of my articles."
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some outlets have chosen to close, such as El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua, after its correspondent, Miroslava Brich, was killed in March.
Others continue to hold out, like "El Maniana" of Nuevo Laredo after its leader was assassinated in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juárez publicly addressed the drug cartels with a front-page editorial entitled "What do you want us to do?"
Some journalists have left their home states or even the country.
It is a painful decision.
In exile, it is difficult to find work, and they continue to look for danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as was apparently the case with photographer Ruben Espinoza, who was killed in 2015, along with four women, in an apartment in Mexico City three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who remain and continue to work are balancing the risks on a daily basis.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he dreads writing about the drug trade.
"Mexico is going to hell and that's why I became a journalist," he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the latest issue was ready to be printed, the publishers of Riodos were sitting on the sidewalk outside the office and drinking beer when suddenly their phones rang at the same time.
A series of shootings between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Mazatlan has left 19 bodies confirmed.
The war continued to escalate, as promised in a series of messages from cartels found in the area.
Sitting on the pavement, they posted the news on the Riodos website via their mobile phone.
The next day, the first page had to be rewritten.
Sirens sounded nearby - another exchange of gunfire in the vicinity.
Bojorquez looked to see if the police officers guarding them were ready to defend themselves.
If they were scared, they showed no sign of it.
Sitting beneath a huge portrait of the late founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was on display throughout Sinaloa, Riodos officers pursued his case.
"How can you think of closing down," Bojorquez said, "if on the very day Javier was killed, the intern asked me to send her outside to report?"
The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, he seems like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
Researchers have revealed that the first remains of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner have been so well preserved that experts have dubbed it the "Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that they were even able to identify that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown - and say that he had, in some ways, a "dark past."
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as "the best-preserved Tyreophorus ever found and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
The fossil is a newly discovered specimen of a nodosaurus that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good fortune has stunned researchers, who call him "truly remarkable."
This herbivore thyreophorus is the best-preserved fossil of its kind ever found, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
He was found by Sean Funk while he was working at Suncor's Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed to be different from the surrounding rock, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrells Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out to find the animal inside the 2,500-foot (1,100-kilogram) rock.
Now that all this hard work has been done, the finished product can be demonstrated.
"You only have to squint a little and you can almost believe he's asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontology Museum, where the creation is being shown.
"It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
Examining its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, despite being covered in shell and resembling a walking tank, was likely to have been exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful shell-covered dinosaur used a red-and-white camouflage to hide from predators, and employed a protective technique known as protective coloring, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow it to merge more quickly with its environment and avoid meeting enemies, experts say, suggesting it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
The 110 million-year-old creature, part of the nodosaurus family, made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum lab technician Mark Mitchell, one of the team members who spent more than 7,000 hours excavating it.
The remarkable preservation of the specimen allowed Dr Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and shell plates on his body.
They found protective coloring, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, meaning that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although protective coloring is common, the discovery came as a surprise because the Borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than today's protective-coloring animals.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivores that evolution chose to camouflage confrontation as a means of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloring - such as deer, zebras, or battleships - are much smaller and more accessible prey, suggesting that the nodosaurus had a serious fight for survival.
"The serious threat from predators to the massive, shell-covered dinosaur shows how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period were," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the dinosaur's scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for clues about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried into the sea, where it sank and lay with its back down on the ocean floor.
Back then, Alberta was as warm as south Florida is now, and rivers and oceans were likely to have spread much farther inland than they are now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
"As a result, the animal looks much the same now as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
It doesn't take much imagination to recreate it, just a little squinting, and you can almost believe he's asleep. "
The Cretaceous period was the era when giant theropods, carnivorous two-legged dinosaurs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, some of its formidable ancestors could have hunted for the thyroid.
They include an acrocantosaurus, a monster measuring 38 feet (11.5 meters) long and weighing six tons.
The scientists, whose latest findings are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was carried into the sea after its death and mummified in silt.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to museum staff, it is the best-preserved thyrophorus in the world, together with the skin and shell, and it is intact, from the snout to the femur bones.
On average, the creatures were about 18 feet (five meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
They were characterized by two twenty-inch spikes protruding from their shoulders.
Researchers believe the herbivore thyreophorus was treading hard on what is now Canada until a spilled river carried it out to sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur preserved its shell to the smallest detail.
The fossilised remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the rugged shell plates along the dinosaur's skull.
As Michael Gresko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is "rare as winning the lottery."
The longer I look at it, the more astounding it seems.
Fossilized remains of skin still cover the rugged shell plates that dot the animal's skull.
His right front leg is stretched out along his side, five fingers on it turned up.
I can count the scales on his sole. "
