How did one activist know the answer to the question "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrel was shocked to the core.
Just a day after arriving in New York on a tourist trip, the St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an apartment rented through Airbnb, browsing the Facebook feed on her phone.
She came across the post of someone from high school.
It said: "The police have just killed an 18-year-old child and he is still lying in the middle of the street."
Noticing that no one else on her feed had memorized the information, puzzled, she shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
Her feed had many posts from a user with the username @ ThePharoah.
The Greater St. Louis rapper tweeted live coverage of the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old who was shot dead by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's lifeless body sprawled out in the street, where it will remain for four hours.
"It's savagery," Ferrel thought.
But death was nothing new for her and her circle.
She put her phone down and later in the evening returned to tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
There were photos of the signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a placard that said, "The Ferguson police officer just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, pulled the trigger of a rifle and shouted, "I'm going to kill you all... animals!"
"It's an unusual situation," Ferrel said at the time.
"It's not the kind of killing that we're used to and that we can call typical.
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and crying. "
She picked up a ticket for the return flight and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11pm, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrel and Ferguson over the next almost three years is the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience from the point of view of people living in a community and filling the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrel drove to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower dress and flower wreath, they recalled a conversation they had had countless times before this morning "about the experience of black people and their situation."
She recalls saying, "Do you remember me telling you how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We're going to Ferguson right now because an 18-year-old boy was killed by a police officer, and that was wrong. "
"I couldn't help but take it," Ferrel said later.
"What is happening today is the culmination of what... happened before.
She should know about it, see it, and be educated on it.
She must not only be well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and position, and what we must do to be free to emancipate ourselves.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she herself does not encounter blatant racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel I would be doing her a disservice by shielding her from it. "
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop on South Florissant Road, a site across the street from a police station that has become something of a tent camp, as activists waited for reports of Officer Darren Wilson's eventual innocence.
There, Ferrel and his daughter joined a local entrepreneur preparing lunch bags.
They collected bags and helped distribute them to protesters.
Little by little, a new type of activism took shape in Ferrel's mind.
"My activism changed completely after August 9," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Minority Nursing Students, and worked on food justice and health inequality among black communities.
"I had no experience as an organizer.
It came on its own. "
A few weeks later, at an evening screening, Ferrel met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her principal cameraman, Lucas Alvarado-Ferrer, "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrel asked, "Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?"
This skepticism was inspired by the many people, often white, who came to the community to benefit from its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don't get the spotlight, and we wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director, Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row.
His involvement aroused sympathy for the project among Ferrel and six other locals with whom the Whose Streets? project team had been in touch in the years since Brown's murder.
"In this documentary, it's not someone talking for us or with us, it's us talking for ourselves," Davis said.
"That was the most important thing for me about how these people will be represented, because that's how I'll be represented."
Although the project was not intended to focus on Ferrel's experience - in an effort to show that the movement "is not about a savior leader, but about how the community comes together," as Folayan put it - it was the most open of the participants in the film.
As a result, Whose Streets? shows unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrel's life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrel said, laughing as she described the first time she saw the finished product.
"But I understood that when you do this kind of work and humanize black people, there must be some level of vulnerability."
Ferrel's story also revisits and highlights the role of black homosexual women in the broader context of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders - those who created the # BlackLivesMatter hashtag on social media after the 2012 shooting of black teenager Trayvon Martin - identify as homosexuals.
"Black gay women in leadership positions support the whole movement," Ferrel said, "and that's because we're constantly fighting on several fronts.
Black homosexual women have to bear all this burden. "
Folayan agreed, noting that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of homosexual black women."
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination," and that Ferrell was not chosen to star in the film because of her distinctive features.
"She was the person who awakened that energy," she said.
"On the other hand, it is no coincidence that it came to the fore because when"
You can feel its energy through the screen. "
Meanwhile, Ferguson has long had no cameras, but complex racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrel will be on probation for another two and a half years for blocking a highway during the demonstration.
She describes the sociopolitical atmosphere of the place she calls home simply: "Bardak."
She still clings to the speech she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains. "
