Emerging similarities: An artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of the room at the Friedman Gallery in New York, people's faces - white, black, and brown, all ineffectually similar - hang from the ceiling on a wire.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clippings from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for famously passing confidential diplomatic cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is called "The Emergence of similarity."
It is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science, and the arts, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident whom Barack Obama commuted just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing Manning's DNA using a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that people with such a genome might have, Dewey-Harborg has created a profound, if difficult-to-read manifesto that focuses not only on the plasticity of DNA data - the different ways in which they are interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also on the concept of identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly said since her teens that she considers herself a woman, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 counts, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were not available, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie in which Manning, wearing a platinum-tinted wig and clearly feeling uncomfortable, sits at the wheel of a car, with which she has come to be associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg completed her 2012 project Stranger Visions with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from the debris and creating images of what those people might look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of a new press exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea couldn't be visited or photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait made from her DNA.
In an unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, "Suppressed Images," illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, who imagined that in the future the president would commute Chelsea's punishment so that she could visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama did decide to release Manning just days after the book's release was a pleasant surprise after seven tough years in a military prison in Kansas.
There is also something profound and powerful in the fact that the exhibition is opening right now, as Donald Trump declares war on people who disclose classified information in government and invents new ways to stoke the Twitter animosity that he is meant to soften.
When asked about the coincidence of the timing, Dewey-Harborg said "nothing happens by accident."
In the artist's statement written on the gallery wall, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a dot above the "i" in her surname) calls for an end to "automatic segregation based on gender, race, sexual orientation, and culture."
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of pencil-written C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist puts it scientifically, delicately), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how remarkably similar we are, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is," said Dewey-Harborg, whose 2007 video work "False Memories" is also on display here.
"DNA data can tell us so many different stories, and 30 of those stories are here."
The last part of the exhibition, which fits in one room, is the aforementioned comic novel.
In it, Manning appears King Kong-style above the US Correctional Barracks with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they will win," it says.
"So never shut up."
"It's a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me," says the Philadelphia-based artist.
'I still get goosebumps when I'm talking about it. '
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person - as presciently depicted in the comics - but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genome simulators, gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is as deliberate as anything in the exhibition down to the height (5 "2, Manning's height) on which the genetic haplogroups were drawn in pencil.
"I used to hang them on the walls, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people," Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
'I wanted them to be like the grassroots movement that formed around Chelsea, the movement that was behind her liberation as well. '
Northwestern University professor and Oxford University employee wanted by police on murder charges
A Northwestern University professor and an Oxford University employee are being hunted nationwide as suspects after a man was found stabbed to death in a luxury Chicago hotel room, police said.
