Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko: "We will fulfill the requirements of the WADA roadmap in the near future"
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko has said that the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) conditions set for the resumption of the work of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) will be met in the near future.
"A certain stage of compliance has been reached and RUSADA has been granted the right to plan and carry out the tests in conjunction with UKAD (UK Anti-Doping Agency).
The WADA roadmap has been updated accordingly, "Mutko said on Thursday.
The Prime Minister commented on the second part of the WADA roadmap to reinstate compliance with the Code, which lists the conditions for the resumption of RUSADA operations and was recently published on the organization's website.
According to Mutko, it contains nothing that would present difficulties for Russia.
"Everything has been announced, everything will be done.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future, "he added.
However, one of the requirements included in the list implies that Russian anti-doping authorities should publicly accept the results of a WADA-commissioned investigation by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren, which alleged that doping in Russian sport was state-controlled.
Addressing the issue, Mutko said: 'We are investigating because our anti-doping system has failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs, and we will not recognize what did not exist. "
Mutko echoed the words of Vitaly Smirnov, head of Russia's independent public anti-doping commission.
On the morning of the same day, in an interview with the Russian publication Rsport, Smirnov acknowledged previous problems in Russian anti-doping structures, but added: "We have repeatedly said that the report contains certain controversial positions and provisions.
Unconditionally, no one is going to accept this report, "Smirnov added.
WADA suspended RUSADA from doping control in November 2015 following a doping scandal.
But in June this year he was allowed to plan and coordinate testing under the supervision of international experts and the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
After visiting the organization's Moscow office in July, WADA Director General Olivier Niggli said RUSADA was "moving in the right direction" toward reinstating its operations.
