The startups that will help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to gauge the level of satisfaction among her e-commerce startup's employees, but the surveys didn't work.
Answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some staff members distrusted the process.
"He was never consistent or objective," said Errett, who runs San Francisco-based Madison Reed, an e-commerce company in the field of hair care.
So she turned to third parties for help.
Now a new kind of HR startup is emerging to help companies figure out how their employees are feeling.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to conduct rapid surveys, address specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and, in some cases, allow informants to bypass top management and contact management directly.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of startup Glint in Redwood City, whose analytics software companies use to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she gained a better understanding of what her employees thought and felt during her three years using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires from certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and visualizes which departments have the most complaints and which managers have low approval ratings, which allows the company to understand why.
Companies are slowly realizing that they need to control the workplace, or else they will become just another Uber that was implicated in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who complained were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire for control is an opportunity for profitable business.
The financial technology portal Let's Talk About Payment estimates that the global governance, regulation, and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
A Denver, Colorado-based startup called Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid Uber's declining reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently appeared among its customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized surveys of staff opinions, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous text-messaging hotline that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if a top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
"The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, Convercent's founder and president.
If a company is found to be mistreating employees or behaving unethically, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee departures, and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
"Ruby Tuesday," a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in 500 locations, has used "Convercent" for more than a year to ensure that employees are aware of rules and procedures, and to offer an easy way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a phone number or email address for the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, the head of legal affairs at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employees "complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that used to be hidden from managers in offices in other cities or states - such as discrimination, harassment, and unfair pay - can be detected and addressed more quickly.
"I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees," said Vitrano, who heads the network's risk management group, Ruby Tuesday.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
According to Quinland, companies began to take employee ethics, values, and engagement more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed for ethical violations in the wake of the Enron affair.
But it was only when "social media went viral" that companies realized that they could not keep their dirty laundry from going viral online.
"Before we started using technology to monitor ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies regular fees for the use of their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity that has won the approval of venture investors, who have backed both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in financing from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing its total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising, given the interconnected nature of companies, culture, and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In highly competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just the minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued, and to dedicate their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work for a company, feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do is paying off, they try harder to make it a success," said Nina McQueen, vice president of global employee benefits and satisfaction at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money when companies in their portfolio are doing well; companies are doing well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it is not surprising that they find support.
As workplace culture experts argue, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data are useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not come quickly enough, or if it does not come at all, frustration can develop and employees lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you have to be willing to have 4,000 conversations," said Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too heavily on data collection.
"Because if you don't go all the way, the staff will be like," Did you hear me?
Don't you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care? "
Errett said Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem with Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it retain employees more effectively in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you're not trying to create a culture of transparency, you're going to lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
