Bruins team has to practice longer after National Student Sports Association cancels twice-a-day workouts
Time is approaching eleven o'clock; a crowd of players from the University of California at Los Angeles lingers to chat on one side of the team's new training fields located on campus.
Some pulled up their T-shirts, exposing their backs, glistening with sweat after a tense first day of training camp.
For many of the team's players, these moments of idleness constitute a mid-day break.
After a three-hour training session, the players will head back to their dormitories to prepare for the final exams, and return to Wasserman's football center the next morning for meetings at 6: 30 a.m.
Shortly before Monday turned into Tuesday, Bruins coach Jim Mora said, "These guys are going to have a meat grinder for the next three days."
The fact that the National Student Sports Association canceled training twice a day, which was designed to reduce the workload for players, actually lengthened their workday - at least until the end of Friday's exams.
So the first three practices of the University of California, Los Angeles team were scheduled to start at 7: 15 p.m. to fit into the players "already busy schedule.
A side effect of not having two workouts a day is more days with one workout, and the Bruins are moving the start of camp by nearly a week from last year and training during summer school for the first time in Mora's six seasons at Westwood.
They are scheduled to hold 18 practices through August 20 before starting formal preparations for their first game of the season against a Texas A & M University team in September.
Mora said he supports a rule change by the National Student Sports Association, even though it adds another item to the tight player schedule.
"For three or four days we give them this huge load, it's a big test," Mora said.
"And they just got over it, they're working, they're great guys.
I think when we get to Saturday and have more time, it's going to be really cool. '
When the camp ends, the University of California at Los Angeles will make workouts closed; no easy task, as its fields are in direct view from the adjacent parking lot and from the nearby Laskin Center, an expensive hotel that has already been bombarded with footballs that have crossed the protective net behind the goal.
Bruins players must occupy a hotel starting this weekend, but Mora admits that when rooms are available during the season, there could be a problem.
"We will have security," Mora said.
'This is a serious problem and I'm not exaggerating the danger by suggesting that someone can rent a room, sit there and video the training.
If you have a video of a training session, it's very serious.
But we will have security there and there will be security at car park number 8.
We will do everything we can with what we have.
I won't worry too much about it.
We have a plan. "
