Facebook steps up fact-checking in fight against fake news
Facebook will increasingly send texts suspected of hoaxes to independent experts and display their findings under original posts, the world's largest social network said Thursday as it tries to combat so-called fake news.
In a statement on its website, the company said it is beginning to use improved machine-learning algorithms to detect possible hoaxes, send them for testing, and possibly display the results of fact-checking under the original post.
Facebook has been criticized as one of the main sources of so-called fake news, which many believe influenced the 2016 US presidential election.
The issue has also been the subject of intense debate in Europe, after French voters were misled by false reports ahead of May's presidential election, and in Germany ahead of September's election declared support for a plan to fine social media if they do not promptly remove hate posts.
In a separate statement in German on Thursday, Facebook said it was testing a new fact-checking algorithm that has been launched in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
"In addition to seeing which posts are challenged by independent reviewers, people want a broader context to make informed judgments about what they are reading and sharing," Sarah Sue, Facebook's News Feed Manager, wrote in her blog.
She added that Facebook would continue to test the "linked articles" feature and work on other changes to the news feed to address the problem of fake news.
Create a comic novel: One castle in English history
In the recent past, the tiny Scotney Castle was featured in the music video "Squeeze," and in the 1970 "s and 1980" s served as a refuge for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years on from his cozy spot in the River Beul valley in Kent, he has observed the tumultuous history around him, and has now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a mop of hair and a penchant for historical documents, to write a comic novel.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
"Castle in England" covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells the story of families who lived in Scotney; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Bryony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes's first book to be based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories, a collection of British Library documents that moved him unexpectedly to his heart.
"I could be moved by just a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites," he says.
"It's his fingerprint"
And letters always smell of smoke, because in those days a fire was lit to illuminate.
And 300 years from now, in the future, you think you're there, too.
Oh, how I love archives! "
For someone so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and living in a castle for four months ("Honestly, I've stayed there a little bit") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days exploring the "new" Victorian castle, browsing the archives and examining the estate's many treasures and antiquities - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had lain in the moat for centuries.
He walked in the park and through the ruins of the old castle, talking to forest rangers, gardeners, and sometimes artists working on illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he would "drink whiskey and sit down to write."
The history of Scotney Castle is not well understood, because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, staff were just beginning to sort through the archive, which he describes as "what the aristocrats had piled up in the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, "but this birch was fought over by two families.
It happens, guys! "
In some of the stories in the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for wider research in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is evidence of a riot at the castle in 1380 in a book called The Knighthoods of Kent and Sussex," says Rhodes.
"The peasant revolt began in these places, and I thought that it was the right place to start.
Maybe they were related? "
Other stories are strongly linked to the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest," which tells the story of a Jesuit priest whom the Durrells family hid in their home for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler," about the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrel, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stoning the coffin (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Durrells are the loved-up Rhodes family of all who inhabited the Scotstoun: "The gentlemen seem to have been a perfect scam, forever getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, the male Durrells solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I think of them as the company of nice guys who know how to look after heiresses of big fortunes. "
After finishing his job at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elämäki, a place where there was a health resort at the beginning of the twentieth century, and then it was overgrown with forest again.
But Scotney remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
'I was like, "Damn, I've got to get back into real life."
Fifteen Largest Banks Choose "Russia"
The conflict in the Association of Russian Banks (ARB) is developing: after Sberbank, VTB, VTB-24, Alfa-Bank, Gazprombank, Rosselkhozbank, Binbank and FC Otkritie, another seven credit institutions are about to leave this public organization.
Thus, organizations that have withdrawn from the ARB will have at least 80 percent of the market.
But it is not just a way out - all banks that have announced a break with the ARB are negotiating with another public organization uniting credit institutions, the Association of Regional Banks "Rossiya," headed by a well-known politician, Anatoly Aksakov, Chairman of the State Duma Committee on Financial Market, who was recognized, by the way, following the results of the last session and the most effective head of the Duma Committee and deputy in terms of the number of draft laws prepared.
The conflict within the ARB began during a discussion in the Federation Council, when the Interregional Banking Council was considering new draft laws, including a new classification of banks according to the size of the authorized capital.
At that time, Garegin Tosunyan, President of ARB, stated that, in the opinion of the Association, this bill is adopted in the interest of the largest banks, which thus try to limit the opportunities of small and medium-sized banks in the regions by intercepting their customers.
Among other complaints, there was also criticism of the Central Bank, which, according to Tosunyan, is not always justifiably revoking the licenses of some banks, to which, however, there was an objection from a representative of the Central Bank: many of the heads of the past banks, particularly Vneshprombank, were members of the governing bodies of the ARB.
Apparently, this exchange of mutually exclusive opinions in a highly sensitive banking environment to relations with the main regulator became a visible reason for the fifteen largest banks, having stated their disagreement with the ARB's policy, to begin preparing to join the Rossiya association, noting that "the effectiveness of the ARB's work is at a low level, and a constructive dialogue within the banking community is not actually being conducted."
Depositors will be better off
Where will it end?
Let us immediately answer the main question, which arises in the event of the slightest disruption or conflict in the banking sector or near it: depositors are not threatened by anything; rather, on the contrary, the reliability of the banking system will be improved.
The head of Rossiya, Anatoly Aksakov, is a high-level professional who is highly regarded in the Central Bank: practically all the Central Bank's management is present at the association's annual events, and all significant legislative initiatives of the regulator pass through expert assessments by the "regions."
In terms of personnel and organization, it is also clear that there will be no major upheaval.
To be sure, ARB finds itself in a difficult financial-management situation after losing such powerful and influential participants with their contributions and lobbying capabilities.
But in this oldest - established in 1991 - organization for the interests of the banking community, there is considerable potential to continue to improve banking legislation and monetary policy in general.
It cannot be said that the Rossiya Association is ready to accept new members under any conditions, judging by the reaction of its head, Anatoly Aksakov ("maybe they will want too much"), who stated on July 21, at a briefing in the press center of the Parliamentary Newspaper, that "literally the next day, representatives of banks that have withdrawn from the ARB asked me to consider the possibility of increasing the potential of our Rossiya Association."
Their proposals are to strengthen bankers "voices on the Association Board, and to pay more attention to new banking technologies.
Negotiations are underway, proposals from both sides are being studied, and the agenda for the Association's extraordinary congress, which will be held in Sochi in mid-September as part of an international banking forum, is being prepared.
That's where we'll find out.
Also, Anatoly Aksakov, stressing that "he is not holding on to his seat," named Georgy Luntovsky, who is leaving in September as Deputy Chairman of the Central Bank, as a possible new head of the renewed Rossiya Association, highly characterizing his business and human qualities.
On August 18, Anatoly Aksakov, who is currently holidaying in Crimea, plans to interrupt his vacation for one day and arrive in Moscow for an extraordinary meeting of the Council of the Rossiya Association, where the agenda of the extraordinary Rossiya congress is scheduled to be considered.
