Andrei Okhlopkov transferred from the cosmodrome
As Kommersant learned, Andrei Okhlopkov, Technical Director of the Vostochny Cosmodrome, started work at Khrunichev State Space Research and Production Center (SKNPC).
Previously, he was de facto engaged in the construction of the Vostochny Cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the management of the Centre for the Operation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (CENKI), he was transferred to a facility in Fili, Moscow, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Okhlopkov will not have a replacement: the post of technical director will most likely be abolished, and the functional functions will be scattered throughout the subdivisions of the ECCI.
Top managers of several space industry enterprises, as well as an employee of the government apparatus, told Kommersant that Andrei Okhlopkov, Technical Director of Vostochny and Deputy General Director of CENKI for Technological Development, had joined Khrunichev State Research and Production Center.
"He has been working in his new position for several weeks," Kommersant industry sources said.
CENKI could not be reached for immediate comment on Thursday, and Mr Okhlopkov was unavailable for comment.
However, Kommersant's information was officially confirmed by SKNPC.
He made a decision to transfer to the post of Director of Production Coordination, the company said. - Andrei Okhlopkov fully fulfilled his task of ensuring the minimum launch time for the first launch at Vostochny Cosmodrome.
Mr. Okhlopkov went to work at CENKI in 2013, having served in the space forces, particularly on Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the "northern" cosmodrome - he held the post of First Deputy Commander with the rank of Colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, at his request, regional merchants received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean up separated parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The technological development responsibilities assigned to him at CENKI applied to various projects, but the main one was the construction of a cosmodrome in the Far East.
In an interview with Kommersant, the then head of the Federal Space Agency, Oleg Ostapenko, bluntly said that the situation on Vostochny "was already critical in October 2013."
The fact is that there was a strategic error in the planning: the completion of construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were scheduled for the same time - the end of 2015.
In order to carry out the launch before the end of the year, the construction was decided to be completed six months earlier and the schedule was changed from December to July 2015.
In order to speed up the process, a trick had to be used: CENKI specialists began to carry out parallel installation of technological equipment at unfinished facilities.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and the postponement (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz took off only on April 28, 2016), this idea paid off, says a Kommersant source at the cosmodrome: "Otherwise, we would still not have carried out a single launch from Vostochniy, but would have been engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly referred to Andrei Okhlopkov as his "cosmic Susanin," but it was from him that he almost always requested information about the progress of construction.
Mr. Okhlopkov is also remembered for his bluntness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of the only performer for the Eastern region and to work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all eggs in one basket of Spetsstroy?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, CENKI has assumed the duties of general contractor in order to complete the construction and installation works at the start-up and maintenance complex by the planned launches in the fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant, the reason for Mr. Okhlopkov's transition to a new job was disagreement with the CENKI leadership on how to complete the construction of the facilities and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as on how to work with subcontractors.
"It was decided that it would be better for everyone," says one of the top managers involved in the construction of Vostochny.
A government official, in turn, calls the decision strange: "He was one of the best specialists, finding an equivalent replacement for him will not be easy."
According to Kommersant, this will not be necessary: the post of technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be spread over subdivisions of the ECCI.
