Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease the GCC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects an estimated 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, causes colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Normally, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the gut ensure that harmful microbes from food do not enter the body.
Cells that can trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance while protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is skewed too much toward inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice with certain bacteria in the gut develop tolerance-boosting cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of the protein - to trigger the emergence of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one bacterial species - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of tolerance-boosting cells.
The more tryptophan was in the mice "diet, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, while studying a variety of tolerance-boosting immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
DNA from the gut cells of mice was sequenced, and six species of bacteria were found, present in mice with immune cells but absent in mice without them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cell received L. reuteri and developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of the fluid - without the bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerance-boosting cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells also halved.
Dr Cervantes-Barragán explains that humans have the same tolerance-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
She says: "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because these cells are responsible for the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the gut.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri have the potential to expand their populations. "
