Reception for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event celebrating American manufacturing cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 event at the White House to showcase American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and top White House officials toured technology products from all fifty states.
The helicopter, made in Connecticut, was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a loader from Mississippi.
According to records from the Marine Corps First Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the division in charge of helicopter operations, the White House Military Office ordered the helicopter's presence on a private order, or "FRAGO," just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn for an "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure you were aware, because this is an unusual, highly publicized event," the commander of HMX-1 wrote in an email to his superiors, the Marine Corps First Deputy Chief of Aviation, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for the event scheduled for 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that day.
The letter adds that if a departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be needed for the return flight, in accordance with operating hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, while the unit's security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records obtained by TIME whether a second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event did not contravene the order.
"Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were told it wasn't," the commander wrote.
"It looks like you have nowhere to go," replied the deputy chief.
The "Made in America" event was announced by the White House as an official event and was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
During the event, the president sought to advance health-care reform, then in the works in the Senate, and touted efforts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are instructed to use them for travel.
But it is unusual to request them solely in the interest of photo opportunity.
Trump was already the subject of controversy in February, when the presidential plane skidded into the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with messages complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is excited about the" Made in America "show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said Deputy White House Press Secretary Lindsey Walters.
HMX-1 crews often carry out training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train the United States president's transportation to the White House to within an inch.
When Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings near the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight made for the "Made in America" event was counted against the crew's monthly training flight requirement.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 extra hours that day as part of "non-presidential support missions."
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits on display at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in organizing the helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Defense Department's hourly rate for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense reimbursement rate for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's records show that the flight time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its base airfield at Quantico Air Force Base in Virginia.
The White House argues that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than that rate.
"Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on an approximate rate of reimbursement is completely wrong," Walters said.
"These indicative rates include manpower, maintenance, and many other irreversible costs, which are included in the annual allocations."
According to a 2015 study by RAND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance, and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase things made in America this week," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suspect, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military hardware that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
So, of course, it is entirely appropriate to pay attention to this. "
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he certainly sat in the driver's seat of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky, joking with the press about the company's own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said. "I have three of them."
